**Complete Research Context:**
Communications Privacy protects content/metadata of comms (calls, texts, emails, IM) from unauthorized access. Key terms: Data Action (e.g., collection, disclosure); Data Processing (lifecycle); Ecosystem (entities/networks); Privacy Breach (unauthorized access); Event (problematic action); Risk (likelihood/impact); Problematic Data Action (adverse effects); Confidentiality (access restrictions); Integrity (guard against modification); E2EE (end-to-end encryption, e.g., Signal Protocol); Metadata (non-content data like timestamps).
NIST Privacy Framework (PRF): Core (5 Functions: Identify [risks], Govern [policies], Control [data actions], Communicate [transparency], Protect [safeguards]); Profiles (org-specific current/target alignments, e.g., 'align comms apps to GDPR'); Tiers (1: Partial [ad-hoc], 2: Risk Informed [approval processes], 3: Repeatable [defined], 4: Managed [proactive], 5: Adaptive [innovative]). Implementation Examples: P-ID-1 (inventory data processing for comms), P-CON-7 (E2EE controls).
Best Practices: E2EE setup (keys exchanged securely), TLS, metadata minimization. Regs: GDPR (data minimization), EARN IT (backdoor risks). Cases: Snowden (metadata harms), Apple-FBI.
Sources: NIST Privacy Framework v1.0 (doi.org/10.6028/NIST.CSWP.011); NISTIR 8259; SP 800-53 (controls); GDPR.eu; EFF.org (E2EE).
